<h2>California Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>California offers some of the most comprehensive solar and energy efficiency incentive programs in the United States, making renewable energy and efficient HVAC systems more affordable for homeowners. The federal Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% tax credit for solar panel installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the full system cost including panels, inverters, mounting equipment, and installation labor, and can be carried forward to future tax years if the credit exceeds current tax liability.</p>

<p>The California Self-Generation Incentive Program (SGIP) provides substantial rebates for battery energy storage systems, offering up to \$1,000 per kilowatt-hour of storage capacity for standard residential applications. Low-income customers and those in disadvantaged communities can receive enhanced rebates up to \$1,200-1,400 per kWh. SGIP also covers fuel cells and other qualifying distributed energy technologies, though funding is limited and operates on a first-come, first-served basis with different steps offering decreasing rebate levels.</p>

<p>Pacific Gas & Electric, Southern California Edison, and San Diego Gas & Electric each offer various rebate programs for energy-efficient HVAC equipment. PG&E's Energy Efficiency Rebates program provides \$500-1,500 for qualifying high-efficiency air conditioners, heat pumps, and smart thermostats. Additional rebates are available for duct sealing, insulation improvements, and whole-house energy efficiency upgrades. Many California municipal utilities and community choice aggregators offer their own incentive programs, sometimes providing more generous rebates than the investor-owned utilities.</p>

<p>California's Disadvantaged Communities Single-Family Affordable Solar Housing (DAC-SASH) program provides upfront rebates for solar installations in low-income households, while the Energy Savings Assistance Program offers free weatherization and HVAC improvements for qualifying low-income customers. Property tax exclusions for solar installations ensure that adding solar panels won't increase property tax assessments, and net energy metering allows homeowners to receive credit for excess solar production fed back into the grid.</p>

